{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-post-js","path":"/html5-video-tag/","result":{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"RGB","feedbackUrl":"https://forms.gle/fCsxvTqoJsx999m79"}},"markdownRemark":{"id":"884a2462-c2fd-59a8-8c72-10f5040caef3","excerpt":"You may have noticed that the number of platforms for tutorials, vlogging, streaming, ADs, shows, and series has been growing fast. The decrease of relativeâ€¦","html":"<p>You may have noticed that the number of platforms for tutorials, vlogging, streaming, <abbr title=\"Advertisement\">ADs</abbr>, shows, and series has been growing fast. The decrease of relative prices for streaming devices like smartphones, smart TVs, combined with stable internet connection availability, helped to boost the demand for video content significantly. Since the industry started to grow, it naturally requires more people to keep it afloat. And I am one of those people - a video engineer.</p>\n<p>I have been doing this for five years already, and I have always found it challenging to find useful information about working with video on the web. This is why I decided to write a series of articles to share my experience on how the video works, and I hope it can serve as a solid source of knowledge.</p>\n<p>This first article will be dedicated to the HTML5 video tag and its basic usage on the web.</p>\n<h2 id=\"html-video-element\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#html-video-element\" aria-label=\"html video element permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a><abbr title=\"Hyper Text Markup Language\">HTML</abbr> Video element</h2>\n<p>The simplest example we can start with is adding a video tag (<a href=\"https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/media.html#the-video-element\" target=\"_self\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">video element, specification section</a>) to the <abbr title=\"Hyper Text Markup Language\">HTML</abbr> code. Adding the following code snippet to your markup code will show a player on the web-page and will allow it to play if the browser supports the content-type:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"html\"><pre class=\"language-html\"><code class=\"language-html\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;</span>video</span> <span class=\"token attr-name\">controls</span> <span class=\"token attr-name\">src</span><span class=\"token attr-value\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">=</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">\"</span>testsrc-720p-24fps.mp4<span class=\"token punctuation\">\"</span></span> <span class=\"token attr-name\">width</span><span class=\"token attr-value\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">=</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">\"</span>480<span class=\"token punctuation\">\"</span></span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">/></span></span></code></pre></div>\n<p>Result screenshot (on macOS Catalina using Google Chrome browser v83):\n<span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 480px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blog/static/7c44c4f0d4f9300c2ead080a9f5eebd7/e85cb/video-with-controls-example.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 56.75675675675676%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"video-with-controls-example\"\n        title=\"video-with-controls-example\"\n        src=\"/blog/static/7c44c4f0d4f9300c2ead080a9f5eebd7/e85cb/video-with-controls-example.png\"\n        srcset=\"/blog/static/7c44c4f0d4f9300c2ead080a9f5eebd7/12f09/video-with-controls-example.png 148w,\n/blog/static/7c44c4f0d4f9300c2ead080a9f5eebd7/e4a3f/video-with-controls-example.png 295w,\n/blog/static/7c44c4f0d4f9300c2ead080a9f5eebd7/e85cb/video-with-controls-example.png 480w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 480px) 100vw, 480px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>As you may see, we have used multiple attributes of the <code class=\"language-text\">&lt;video /&gt;</code> tag. One of them is <code class=\"language-text\">controls</code>. If present, the out-of-the-box browser will offer <abbr title=\"User Interface\">UI</abbr> to control video playback (play, pause), current playback position and duration, progress bar, seeking, volume control, download, toggle full-screen mode, toggle closed captions, and toggle the picture in picture mode.</p>\n<h3 id=\"apis-and-events\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#apis-and-events\" aria-label=\"apis and events permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>APIs and Events</h3>\n<p>Because the video tag is a media element, it has various <a href=\"https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/media.html#htmlmediaelement\" target=\"_self\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">APIs</a> and <a href=\"https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/media.html#mediaevents\" target=\"_self\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">events</a> which are accessible through JavaScript:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"js\"><pre class=\"language-js\"><code class=\"language-js\"><span class=\"token comment\">// Adding some event listeners</span>\nelVideo<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">addEventListener</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token string\">'volumechange'</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> console<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>log<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\nelVideo<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">addEventListener</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token string\">'pause'</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> console<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>log<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n\n<span class=\"token comment\">// Calling method `pause`, pause the playback</span>\nelVideo<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">pause</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n\n<span class=\"token comment\">// Getting volume level</span>\nelVideo<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>volume<span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token comment\">// Setting volume level</span>\nelVideo<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>volume <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> <span class=\"token number\">0.5</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>A good demonstration of HTML5 Video APIs and Events could be found on <a href=\"https://www.w3.org/2010/05/video/mediaevents.html\" target=\"_self\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">w3.org page</a>.</p>\n<h3 id=\"what-is-next\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#what-is-next\" aria-label=\"what is next permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>What is next</h3>\n<p>Most video players we see now on the web, and other platforms have a custom <abbr title=\"User Interface\">UI</abbr> and different sophisticated features on top of the video tag. For example, live streaming, advertising support, closed captions, auto-switching between qualities, and chapters (one of the new features YouTube has). To be able to implement the functionality described above as well as something new, we need to learn more specifications. A good specification to start with would be Media Source Extensions (<abbr title=\"Media Source Extensions\">MSE</abbr>), which will be the topic we will dig into next.</p>","frontmatter":{"title":"Intro to the Video Technologies in the Web Applications","date":"June 10, 2020","description":"About HTML5 video tag"},"fields":{"readingTime":{"text":"3 min read"}}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/html5-video-tag/","previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/init/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Init","tags":["about","blog"]}},"next":null}}}